14. Self Invoking Function (IIFE)
Simple Meaning

Normally, we create a function and then call it.

function greet() {
    console.log("Hello");
}

greet();

Output

Hello

Here,

First we created the function.
Then we called it.
Self Invoking Function

Sometimes we want the function to run immediately after it is created.

(function () {
    console.log("Hello");
})();

Output

Hello

Notice:

We never wrote

greet();

Still it executed automatically.

That's why it is called Self Invoking Function or IIFE (Immediately Invoked Function Expression).

Real-life Analogy

Imagine a firecracker.

Normally,

Buy firecracker → Light it → It explodes.

Self Invoking Function is like

Buy a firecracker that automatically explodes as soon as you touch it.

Interview Answer

A Self Invoking Function is a function that executes immediately after it is created.

15. call(), apply(), bind()

This is one of the most asked interview questions.

First understand one thing.

Problem
function introduce() {
    console.log(this.name);
}

Now

let person = {
    name: "Lucky"
};

How can we make

this = person

JavaScript gives us

call()
apply()
bind()
call()

Runs the function immediately.

Arguments are passed one by one.

function greet(city) {
    console.log(this.name + " from " + city);
}

let person = {
    name: "Lucky"
};

greet.call(person, "Mathura");

Output

Lucky from Mathura
apply()

Exactly same as call()

Difference

Arguments are passed inside an array.

greet.apply(person, ["Mathura"]);

Output

Lucky from Mathura
bind()

This one is different.

It does NOT run immediately.

Instead,

It returns a new function.

let newFunction = greet.bind(person, "Mathura");

newFunction();

Output

Lucky from Mathura
Easy Memory Trick
call()

Runs immediately
Arguments separately

-----------------------

apply()

Runs immediately
Arguments inside array

-----------------------

bind()

Does NOT run
Returns a new function
Interview Answer

call() and apply() invoke the function immediately. bind() returns a new function. call() takes arguments separately, whereas apply() takes them as an array.

