19. Scope

Scope means

"Where can I use this variable?"

Global Scope
let name="Lucky";

function show(){
    console.log(name);
}

Output

Lucky

Global variables can be used anywhere.

Function Scope
function test(){

let age=22;

}

console.log(age);

Output

Reference Error

Because age lives only inside the function.

Block Scope
if(true){

let city="Mathura";

}

console.log(city);

Output

Reference Error

Because let is block scoped.

Real-life Analogy

Imagine a house.

Global Scope

Whole house

Everyone can use it.

Function Scope

Only one room

People inside that room can use it.

Block Scope

Only one cupboard

Even smaller area.

Scope Chain

Suppose

let country="India";

function outer(){

let state="UP";

function inner(){

console.log(country);
console.log(state);

}

inner();

}

outer();

How does JavaScript find variables?

It searches like this

Current Function

↓

Parent Function

↓

Global

↓

Not Found

↓

Reference Error

This searching process is called

Scope Chain

Interview Answer

Scope decides where a variable can be accessed. Scope Chain is the process JavaScript uses to search for variables from inner scope to outer scope.

20. Closure (Very Important)

Closure is one of the most important JavaScript interview topics.

Suppose

function outer(){

let count=0;

return function(){

count++;

console.log(count);

}

}

let counter=outer();

counter();

counter();

counter();

Output

1

2

3

Question

How is count still alive?

Because the inner function remembers variables from its outer function even after the outer function has finished executing.

This is called a Closure.

Real-life Analogy

Imagine your mother packs lunch for you before you leave home.

Even though you are no longer at home, you still have the lunch with you.

Similarly, the inner function carries ("remembers") the outer variables even after the outer function has finished.

Interview Answer

A closure is a function that remembers and can access variables from its outer scope even after the outer function has finished executing.

